instances.text: CAPS_V 206-001 - Fundamentals of Physiology in Human Health and Disease II

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
This course explores the conflictual cultural history of Central and Eastern Europe from the eighteenth century to the present. We will investigate the historical roots of present-day conflicts, such as the fight for political stability on the Balkans, the struggle for Ukrainian lands, and the latent state of war in the Caucasus. Classes will be dedicated to lectures on and discussion of films and literary texts that reflect on these issues.

More course information here

Check out more courses from the Department of Central, Eastern and Northern European Studies Click here

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Gender & Sexuality in Central, Eastern, and Northern European Literature and Culture 
In this course, we will explore how discourses on gender and sexuality shaped and were shaped by 19th- and early-20th-century literature and culture. We will read select short prose, drama, and novels from central, eastern, and northern Europe. We will consider how these works relate to emergent sexological writings, women’s rights debates, emergent modern subjectivities (e.g., new woman, queer), and political movements. Throughout the course, we will also consider the relevance of these literary traditions for our current moment. To this end, each student will present on a contemporary news item that connects to issues of gender and sexuality in the contemporary moment. Students will then turn this presentation and the class discussion it generates into a 500-word Blog Post. The class will thus build a public record of your interrogation of issues of gender and nation as it connects to modern issues via the publication of a special issue of the German Program’s Undergraduate Online Journal Augenblick 

Interested in learning about other courses offered in the Department of Central, Eastern and Northern European Studies? Click here

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
CENS 202: The Literature of Interior Spaces 
Private homes, hotels, factories, offices and prisons: this semester, we will explore interior spaces as cultural and political subjects in 19th and 20th c. literature, film and art - from Kafka’s carceral bedrooms to Grete Lihotzky’s rationalized domestic architecture, and from Murnau’s hotel lobbies to the office-worlds in the prose of New Objectivity. In addition to reading fiction and poetry, we will explore works by Bauhaus artists and architects and watch Weimar-era Kammerspielfilme (“chamber dramas”). This course is taught in English.

Interested in checking out other courses in the Department of Central, Eastern and Northern European Studies? Click here
